properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Lake effect snow squalls expected today through Wednesday morning. In the wake of a cold front, a blast of cold arctic air is expected to flow over the relatively warm waters of Lake Huron today. Flurries and local snow squalls are expected to begin this morning and continue into Wednesday morning. Local snowfall amounts 10 to 15 cm are possible today and amounts of 20 to 30 cm are possible tonight into Wednesday morning. Local blowing snow reducing visibilities to near zero will also be a concern. Local snow squalls are expected to taper off when the winds shift to southwest Wednesday afternoon. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Total snowfall: 20 to 40 cm possible. Locations: Hopedale and vicinity, Postville - Makkovik. Time span: overnight tonight until Thursday morning. Remarks: The snow will be accompanied by strong north to northeasterly winds gusting up to 70 km/h on Wednesday giving reduced visibilities in blowing snow. As a result, this watch is likely to be upgraded to a warning in subsequent forecasts later today. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Approaching storm to give mixed precipitation Tuesday and Tuesday night. A developing low pressure system will affect Prince Edward Island beginning tonight. Precipitation will begin as snow tonight and change to rain on Tuesday morning. Currently, 5 to 10 centimetres of snowfall is forecast for Prince County and lower amounts further to the east. Total rainfall accumulations near 25 millimetres are expected on Tuesday and Tuesday night, although it is possible that higher amounts may fall in localized areas. The rain is expected to change to flurries early Wednesday morning as cold westerly winds move into the region and temperatures quickly fall below freezing. Driving conditions may become icy as the cold air and flurries move in. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions in snow and mixed precipitation late tonight and Tuesday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to PEstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #PEStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Storm moving into region will bring significant rainfall starting this morning and extending into Wednesday morning. A developing system will affect Nova Scotia beginning early this morning. Over northern areas of the province, precipitation began with a short period of snow, which now has switched to rain in the southwest. Total snowfall accumulations are forecast to be less than 5 centimetres. The rain will spread over the province by mid-day and will persist tonight. Rainfall warnings have been issued for the most of mainland Nova Scotia with the exception of the Annapolis Valley region and the Cobequid Peninsula. It is possible that these may be extended to other parts Nova Scotia as the system approaches, should the forecast track or intensity of the system change. Rain will change to flurries over western Nova Scotia late tonight night as cold westerly winds move into the region and temperatures quickly fall below freezing. Driving conditions may become icy overnight or Wednesday morning as the cold air and flurries push eastward across the province. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions tonight and Tuesday morning in areas of northern mainland Nova Scotia and northwestern Cape Breton receiving snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Storm moving into the region will bring significant rainfall today and tonight. Rain has begun over southwestern Nova Scotia and will spread across the province today, and will continue into tonight. Total rainfall accumulations are expected to be quite variable, with forecast amounts ranging from 30 to 65 mm and locally higher amounts possible along parts of the Atlantic coast. Rain will change to flurries over western Nova Scotia overnight into Wednesday as cold westerly winds move into the region and temperatures quickly fall below freezing. Driving conditions may become icy overnight or Wednesday morning as the cold air and flurries push eastward across the province. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Snow, ice pellets, and freezing rain to northwestern New Brunswick today. Snow will be heavy at times today, and is forecast to become mixed with ice pellets or freezing rain over portions of these regions, except for Madawaska County and Restigouche County where precipitation is expected to remain as snow throughout the event. Precipitation is forecast to taper to scattered flurries this evening. In addition to the 5 to 10 cm that fell overnight, further snowfall amounts of 20 to 35 cm are expected today and tonight. The travelling public are urged to prepare for potentially difficult driving conditions in snow and mixed precipitation. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
